Introduction

Support Vector Machines.

Support Vector Machines (SVMs) are a type of supervised learning algorithm that can be used for classification or regression tasks. The main idea behind SVMs is to find a hyperplane that maximally separates the different classes in the training data. This is done by finding the hyperplane that has the largest margin, which is defined as the distance between the hyperplane and the closest data points from each class. Once the hyperplane is determined, new data can be classified by determining on which side of the hyperplane it falls. SVMs are particularly useful when the data has many features, and/or when there is a clear margin of separation in the data.

Hyperplanes are decision boundaries that help classify the data points. Data points falling on either side of the hyperplane can be attributed to different classes. Also, the dimension of the hyperplane depends upon the number of features. If the number of input features is 2, then the hyperplane is just a line. If the number of input features is 3, then the hyperplane becomes a two-dimensional plane. It becomes difficult to imagine when the number of features exceeds 3.

SVM A Comprehensive Synthesis of Current Research and Future Directions.

  1. Early Prediction of Dementia Using Feature Extraction Battery(FEB) and Optimized Support Vector Machine (SVM) for Classification

    The research focuses on early dementia prediction using machine learning (ML), specifically the optimized support vector machine (SVM) FEB-SVM model. The study addresses the limitations of existing ML models by adding Adaptive Synthetic Sampling (ADASYN) bias and introduces new feature extraction (FEB) techniques to improve accuracy. The data is collected from the Swedish National Survey on Aging and Care (SNAC), and the accuracy of the proposed FEB-SVM model is 6% better than the traditional SVM. The model is trained on a dataset of 726 participants, showing 98.28% training accuracy and 93.92% testing accuracy. The study outperforms 12 state-of-the-art ML models in predicting dementia, demonstrating its effectiveness in early diagnosis. The methodology includes data processing, feature extraction using LDA, ICA, PCA, LLE, and t-SNE, unbalanced class treatment using ADASYN, and SVM hyperparameter optimization using grid search.

  2. New incremental SVM algorithms for human activity recognition in smart homes

    The paper introducesÂ incremental SVM methods that improve the classification performance of SVM in the context of smart home human activity detection. Two characteristic extraction techniques are proposed: refining dependent sensor extraction and focusing on the last sensor event. Additional SVM methods include a cluster-based approach (IncSucc) to remove redundant information from new pieces and a similarity-based approach to identify and reject support vectors and new strong similarities. Simulations on Aruba and Tulum datasets show the feasibility and improvement of the proposed methods in real-time learning and classification, and similarity-based incremental learning is significantly faster. This approach also addresses the challenge of reducing data and support vectors incrementally for efficient model development.

  3. A credit risk assessment model based on SVM for small and medium enterprises in supply chain finance

    Supply Chain Finance (SCF) is the field in which financial services providers assist customers and suppliers in managing their working capital. Leading supply chain companies in this system ensure financing for Small and Medium Businesses (SMEs). This study suggests an index method that takes into account the credit standing of major corporations and their links with small and medium-sized firms in order to evaluate credit risks in SCF. Support Vector Machine (SVM) and BP Neural Network-based credit risk models are contrasted. More accurate assessments of SME credit risk by banks and the possibility of loosening lending limitations on SMEs are made possible by the higher efficiency of the SVM model. In general, the SVM model and the SCF credit risk assessment index system provide banks with the best possible combination for assessing the credit risk of SMEs.

  4. Multi-disease prediction model using improved SVM-radial bias technique in healthcare monitoring system

    This work focuses on using machine learning to predict diseases in the healthcare sector, specifically using the enhanced SVM-Radial bias kernel approach. In an era where information is extremely valuable, the healthcare industry produces a lot of data that includes patient information and disease-related data. By analyzing this vast amount of medical data, the suggested generic architecture aims to reveal underlying illness patterns and enable personalized treatment. Particularly, a fewer number of attributes from datasets on diabetes, heart disease, and chronic kidney disease were tested in this study. The enhanced SVM-Radial bias kernel method outperformed other machine learning approaches in R studio, including SVM-Linear, SVM-Polynomial, Random Forest, and Decision Tree. Notably, for the datasets on chronic kidney disease, diabetes, and heart disease, respectively, this approach showed astounding accuracy rates of 98.3%, 98.7%, and 89.9%. The results mentioned above highlight the effectiveness of support vector machines (SVM) in personalized healthcare and disease prediction.
